# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kubernetes-operators
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automation includes the use of various equipment and control systems such as machinery, processes in factories, boilers, and heat-treating ovens, switching on telephone networks, steering, stabilization of ships, aircraft and other applications and vehicles with reduced human intervention.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Examples range from a household thermostat controlling a boiler to a large industrial control system with tens of thousands of input measurements and output control signals.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In the simplest type of an automatic control loop, a controller compares a measured value of a process with a desired set value and processes the resulting error signal to change some input to the process, in such a way that the process stays at its set point despite disturbances.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] This closed-loop control is an application of negative feedback to a system.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The mathematical basis of control theory began in the 18th century and advanced rapidly in the 20th.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The term *automation*, inspired by the earlier word *automatic* (coming from *automaton*), was not widely used before 1947, when Ford established an automation department.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] It was during this time that the industry was rapidly adopting feedback controllers, Technological advancements introduced in the 1930s revolutionized various industries significantly.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The World Bank's World Development Report of 2019 shows evidence that the new industries and jobs in the technology sector outweigh the economic effects of workers being displaced by automation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Job losses and downward mobility blamed on automation have been cited as one of many factors in the resurgence of nationalist, protectionist and populist politics in the US, UK and France, among other countries since the 2010s.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] It was a preoccupation of the Greeks and Arabs (in the period between about 300 BC and about 1200 AD) to keep an accurate track of time.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In Ptolemaic Egypt, about 270 BC, Ctesibius described a float regulator for a water clock, a device not unlike the ball and cock in a modern flush toilet.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] This was the earliest feedback-controlled mechanism.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The appearance of the mechanical clock in the 14th century made the water clock and its feedback control system obsolete.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The Persian Banū Mūsā brothers, in their *Book of Ingenious Devices* (850 AD), described a number of automatic controls.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Two-step level controls for fluids, a form of discontinuous variable structure controls, were developed by the Banu Musa brothers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] They also described a feedback controller.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The design of feedback control systems up through the Industrial Revolution was by trial-and-error, together with a great deal of engineering intuition.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] It was not until the mid-19th century that the stability of feedback control systems was analyzed using mathematics, the formal language of automatic control theory.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the seventeenth century, and used to adjust the gap between millstones.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Another control mechanism was used to tent the sails of windmills.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Also in 1745, Jacques de Vaucanson invented the first automated loom.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Around 1800, Joseph Marie Jacquard created a punch-card system to program looms.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In 1771 Richard Arkwright invented the first fully automated spinning mill driven by water power, known at the time as the water frame.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] An automatic flour mill was developed by Oliver Evans in 1785, making it the first completely automated industrial process.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Bunce of England in 1784 as part of a model steam crane.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The governor could not actually hold a set speed; the engine would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Also, there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] As a consequence, engines equipped with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed, such as cotton spinning.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Several improvements to the governor, plus improvements to valve cut-off timing on the steam engine, made the engine suitable for most industrial uses before the end of the 19th century.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Advances in the steam engine stayed well ahead of science, both thermodynamics and control theory.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The governor received relatively little scientific attention until James Clerk Maxwell published a paper that established the beginning of a theoretical basis for understanding control theory.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Relay logic was introduced with factory electrification, which underwent rapid adaptation from 1900 through the 1920s.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Central electric power stations were also undergoing rapid growth and the operation of new high-pressure boilers, steam turbines and electrical substations created a great demand for instruments and controls.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Central control rooms became common in the 1920s, but as late as the early 1930s, most process controls were on-off.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Operators typically monitored charts drawn by recorders that plotted data from instruments.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] To make corrections, operators manually opened or closed valves or turned switches on or off.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Control rooms also used color-coded lights to send signals to workers in the plant to manually make certain changes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The development of the electronic amplifier during the 1920s, which was important for long-distance telephony, required a higher signal-to-noise ratio, which was solved by negative feedback noise cancellation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] This and other telephony applications contributed to the control theory.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flügge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic controls, which found military applications during the Second World War to fire control systems and aircraft navigation systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Controllers, which were able to make calculated changes in response to deviations from a set point rather than on-off control, began being introduced in the 1930s.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Controllers allowed manufacturing to continue showing productivity gains to offset the declining influence of factory electrification.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Factory productivity was greatly increased by electrification in the 1920s.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Alexander Field notes that spending on non-medical instruments increased significantly from 1929 to 1933 and remained strong thereafter.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The First and Second World Wars saw major advancements in the field of mass communication and signal processing.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Other key advances in automatic controls include differential equations, stability theory and system theory (1938), frequency domain analysis (1940), ship control (1950), and stochastic analysis (1941).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In 1959 Texaco's Port Arthur Refinery became the first chemical plant to use digital control.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Conversion of factories to digital control began to spread rapidly in the 1970s as the price of computer hardware fell.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The automatic telephone switchboard was introduced in 1892 along with dial telephones.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] By 1929, 31.9% of the Bell system was automatic.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automatic telephone switching originally used vacuum tube amplifiers and electro-mechanical switches, which consumed a large amount of electricity.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Call volume eventually grew so fast that it was feared the telephone system would consume all electricity production, prompting Bell Labs to begin research on the transistor.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The logic performed by telephone switching relays was the inspiration for the digital computer.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The first commercially successful glass bottle-blowing machine was an automatic model introduced in 1905.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The machine, operated by a two-man crew working 12-hour shifts, could produce 17,280 bottles in 24 hours, compared to 2,880 bottles made by a crew of six men and boys working in a shop for a day.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The cost of making bottles by machine was 10 to 12 cents per gross compared to $1.80 per gross by the manual glassblowers and helpers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives were developed using control theory.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Sectional electric drives are used on different sections of a machine where a precise differential must be maintained between the sections.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In steel rolling, the metal elongates as it passes through pairs of rollers, which must run at successively faster speeds.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In paper making paper, the sheet shrinks as it passes around steam-heated drying arranged in groups, which must run at successively slower speeds.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The first application of a sectional electric drive was on a paper machine in 1919.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] One of the most important developments in the steel industry during the 20th century was continuous wide strip rolling, developed by Armco in 1928.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Before automation, many chemicals were made in batches.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In 1930, with the widespread use of instruments and the emerging use of controllers, the founder of Dow Chemical Co. was advocating continuous production.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Self-acting machine tools that displaced hand dexterity so they could be operated by boys and unskilled laborers were developed by James Nasmyth in the 1840s.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Machine tools were automated with Numerical control (NC) using punched paper tape in the 1950s.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] This soon evolved into computerized numerical control (CNC).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Today extensive automation is practiced in practically every type of manufacturing and assembly process.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Robots are especially useful in hazardous applications like automobile spray painting.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Robots are also used to assemble electronic circuit boards.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automotive welding is done with robots and automatic welders are used in applications like pipelines.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] With the advent of the space age in 1957, controls design, particularly in the United States, turned away from the frequency-domain techniques of classical control theory and backed into the differential equation techniques of the late 19th century, which were couched in the time domain.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] During the 1940s and 1950s, German mathematician Irmgard Flugge-Lotz developed the theory of discontinuous automatic control, which became widely used in hysteresis control systems such as navigation systems, fire-control systems, and electronics.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Through Flugge-Lotz and others, the modern era saw time-domain design for nonlinear systems (1961), navigation (1960), optimal control and estimation theory (1962), nonlinear control theory (1969), digital control and filtering theory (1974), and the personal computer (1983).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Perhaps the most cited advantage of automation in industry is that it is associated with faster production and cheaper labor costs.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Another benefit could be that it replaces hard, physical, or monotonous work.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Additionally, tasks that take place in hazardous environments or that are otherwise beyond human capabilities can be done by machines, as machines can operate even under extreme temperatures or in atmospheres that are radioactive or toxic.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] They can also be maintained with simple quality checks.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] However, at the time being, not all tasks can be automated, and some tasks are more expensive to automate than others.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Initial costs of installing the machinery in factory settings are high, and failure to maintain a system could result in the loss of the product itself.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automation primarily describes machines replacing human action, but it is also loosely associated with mechanization, machines replacing human labor.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The paradox of automation says that the more efficient the automated system, the more crucial the human contribution of the operators.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Humans are less involved, but their involvement becomes more critical.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Lisanne Bainbridge, a cognitive psychologist, identified these issues notably in her widely cited paper "Ironies of Automation." If an automated system has an error, it will multiply that error until it is fixed or shut down.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] A fatal example of this was Air France Flight 447, where a failure of automation put the pilots into a manual situation they were not prepared for.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Many roles for humans in industrial processes presently lie beyond the scope of automation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Human-level pattern recognition, language comprehension, and language production ability are well beyond the capabilities of modern mechanical and computer systems (but see *Watson computer*).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Tasks requiring subjective assessment or synthesis of complex sensory data, such as scents and sounds, as well as high-level tasks such as strategic planning, currently require human expertise.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In many cases, the use of humans is more cost-effective than mechanical approaches even where the automation of industrial tasks is possible.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Therefore, algorithmic management as the digital rationalization of human labor instead of its substitution has emerged as an alternative technological strategy.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Overcoming these obstacles is a theorized path to post-scarcity economics.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] As of 2025-2026, real-world deployment of advanced robotics has revealed critical infrastructure limitations, such as "battery-life bottlenecks" (typically 2–4 hours of operation per charge) and the requirement for high-bandwidth Wi-Fi and specialized flooring for reliable function.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Additionally, robots continue to struggle with unpredictable human-made obstructions, which still necessitate human intervention to maintain operational flow.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Increased automation often causes workers to feel anxious about losing their jobs as technology renders their skills or experience unnecessary.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Early in the Industrial Revolution, when inventions like the steam engine were making some job categories expendable, workers forcefully resisted these changes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Luddites, for instance, were English textile workers who protested the introduction of weaving machines by destroying them.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] More recently, some residents of Chandler, Arizona, have slashed tires and pelted rocks at a self-driving car, in protest over the cars' perceived threat to human safety and job prospects.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The relative anxiety about automation reflected in opinion polls seems to correlate closely with the strength of organized labor in that region or nation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] According to one estimate, 47% of all current jobs in the US have the potential to be fully automated by 2033.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Furthermore, wages and educational attainment appear to be strongly negatively correlated with an occupation's risk of being automated.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Erik Brynjolfsson and Andrew McAfee argue that "there's never been a better time to be a worker with special skills or the right education, because these people can use technology to create and capture value.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Research by Carl Benedikt Frey and Michael Osborne of the Oxford Martin School argued that employees engaged in "tasks following well-defined procedures that can easily be performed by sophisticated algorithms" are at risk of displacement, and 47% of jobs in the US were at risk.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The study, released as a working paper in 2013 and published in 2017, predicted that automation would put low-paid physical occupations most at risk, by surveying a group of colleagues on their opinions.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] However, according to a study published in *McKinsey Quarterly* in 2015 the impact of computerization in most cases is not the replacement of employees but the automation of portions of the tasks they perform.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The methodology of the McKinsey study has been heavily criticized for being intransparent and relying on subjective assessments.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The methodology of Frey and Osborne has been subjected to criticism, as lacking evidence, historical awareness, or credible methodology.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Additionally, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) found that across the 21 OECD countries, 9% of jobs are automatable.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Based on a formula by Gilles Saint-Paul, an economist at Toulouse 1 University, the demand for unskilled human capital declines at a slower rate than the demand for skilled human capital increases.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In the long run and for society as a whole it has led to cheaper products, lower average work hours, and new industries forming (i.e., robotics industries, computer industries, design industries).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] These new industries provide many high salary skill-based jobs to the economy.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] By 2030, between 3 and 14 percent of the global workforce will be forced to switch job categories due to automation eliminating jobs in an entire sector.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] While the number of jobs lost to automation is often offset by jobs gained from technological advances, the same type of job loss is not the same one replaced and that leading to increasing unemployment in the lower-middle class.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] This occurs largely in the US and developed countries where technological advances contribute to higher demand for highly skilled labor but demand for middle-wage labor continues to fall.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Economists call this trend "income polarization" where unskilled labor wages are driven down and skilled labor is driven up and it is predicted to continue in developed economies.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Lights-out manufacturing is a production system with no human workers, to eliminate labor costs.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] It grew in popularity in the U.S. when General Motors in 1982 implemented humans "hands-off" manufacturing to "replace risk-averse bureaucracy with automation and robots".
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] However, the factory never reached full "lights out" status.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The costs of automation to the environment are different depending on the technology, product or engine automated.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] There are automated engines that consume more energy resources from the Earth in comparison with previous engines and vice versa.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Hazardous operations, such as oil refining, the manufacturing of industrial chemicals, and all forms of metal working, were always early contenders for automation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The automation of vehicles could prove to have a substantial impact on the environment, although the nature of this impact could be beneficial or harmful depending on several factors.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Because automated vehicles are much less likely to get into accidents compared to human-driven vehicles, some precautions built into current models (such as anti-lock brakes or laminated glass) would not be required for self-driving versions.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Removal of these safety features reduces the weight of the vehicle, and coupled with more precise acceleration and braking, as well as fuel-efficient route mapping, can increase fuel economy and reduce emissions.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Despite this, some researchers theorize that an increase in the production of self-driving cars could lead to a boom in vehicle ownership and usage, which could potentially negate any environmental benefits of self-driving cars if they are used more frequently.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automation of homes and home appliances is also thought to impact the environment.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] This study, along with others, indicated that the smart home's ability to monitor and adjust consumption levels would reduce unnecessary energy usage.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] However, some research suggests that smart homes might not be as efficient as non-automated homes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] A more recent study has indicated that, while monitoring and adjusting consumption levels do decrease unnecessary energy use, this process requires monitoring systems that also consume an amount of energy.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The energy required to run these systems sometimes negates their benefits, resulting in little to no ecological benefit.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Another major shift in automation is the increased demand for flexibility and convertibility in manufacturing processes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Manufacturers are increasingly demanding the ability to easily switch from manufacturing Product A to manufacturing Product B without having to completely rebuild the production lines.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Flexibility and distributed processes have led to the introduction of Automated Guided Vehicles with Natural Features Navigation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Former analog-based instrumentation was replaced by digital equivalents which can be more accurate and flexible, and offer greater scope for more sophisticated configuration, parametrization, and operation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] This was accompanied by the fieldbus revolution which provided a networked (i.e. a single cable) means of communicating between control systems and field-level instrumentation, eliminating hard-wiring.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Discrete manufacturing plants adopted these technologies fast.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The more conservative process industries with their longer plant life cycles have been slower to adopt and analog-based measurement and control still dominate.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The growing use of Industrial Ethernet on the factory floor is pushing these trends still further, enabling manufacturing plants to be integrated more tightly within the enterprise, via the internet if necessary.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Global competition has also increased demand for Reconfigurable Manufacturing Systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Engineers can now have numerical control over automated devices.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The result has been a rapidly expanding range of applications and human activities.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Computer-aided technologies (or CAx) now serve as the basis for mathematical and organizational tools used to create complex systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Notable examples of CAx include computer-aided design (CAD software) and computer-aided manufacturing (CAM software).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The improved design, analysis, and manufacture of products enabled by CAx has been beneficial for industry.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Information technology, together with industrial machinery and processes, can assist in the design, implementation, and monitoring of control systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] One example of an industrial control system is a programmable logic controller (PLC).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] PLCs are specialized hardened computers which are frequently used to synchronize the flow of inputs from (physical) sensors and events with the flow of outputs to actuators and events.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Human-machine interfaces (HMI) or computer human interfaces (CHI), formerly known as *man-machine interfaces*, are usually employed to communicate with PLCs and other computers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Service personnel who monitor and control through HMIs can be called by different names.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In the industrial process and manufacturing environments, they are called operators or something similar.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In boiler houses and central utility departments, they are called *stationary engineers*.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Host simulation software (HSS) is a commonly used testing tool that is used to test the equipment software.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] HSS is used to test equipment performance concerning factory automation standards (timeouts, response time, processing time).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Cognitive automation, as a subset of AI, is an emerging genus of automation enabled by cognitive computing.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Its primary concern is the automation of clerical tasks and workflows that consist of structuring unstructured data.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Cognitive automation relies on multiple disciplines: natural language processing, real-time computing, machine learning algorithms, big data analytics, and evidence-based learning.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Artificially intelligent computer-aided design (CAD) can use text-to-3D, image-to-3D, and video-to-3D to automate in 3D modeling.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] AI CAD libraries could also be developed using linked open data of schematics and diagrams.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Ai CAD assistants are used as tools to help streamline workflow.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Technologies like solar panels, wind turbines, and other renewable energy sources—together with smart grids, micro-grids, battery storage—can automate power production.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Many agricultural operations are automated with machinery and equipment to improve their diagnosis, decision-making and/or performing.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Agricultural automation can relieve the drudgery of agricultural work, improve the timeliness and precision of agricultural operations, raise productivity and resource-use efficiency, build resilience, and improve food quality and safety.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Increased productivity can free up labour, allowing agricultural households to spend more time elsewhere.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The technological evolution in agriculture has resulted in progressive shifts to digital equipment and robotics.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization using engine power automates the performance of agricultural operations such as ploughing and milking.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] With digital automation technologies, it also becomes possible to automate diagnosis and decision-making of agricultural operations.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] For example, autonomous crop robots can harvest and seed crops, while drones can gather information to help automate input application.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Motorized mechanization has generally increased in recent years.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Sub-Saharan Africa is the only region where the adoption of motorized mechanization has stalled over the past decades.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automation technologies are increasingly used for managing livestock, though evidence on adoption is lacking.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Adoption is likely mostly in Northern Europe, and likely almost absent in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automated feeding machines for both cows and poultry also exist, but data and evidence regarding their adoption trends and drivers is likewise scarce.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Many supermarkets and even smaller stores are rapidly introducing self-checkout systems reducing the need for employing checkout workers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In the U.S., the retail industry employs 15.9 million people as of 2017 (around 1 in 9 Americans in the workforce).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Globally, an estimated 192 million workers could be affected by automation according to research by Eurasia Group.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Online shopping could be considered a form of automated retail as the payment and checkout are through an automated online transaction processing system, with the share of online retail accounting jumping from 5.1% in 2011 to 8.3% in 2016.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] However, two-thirds of books, music, and films are now purchased online.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In addition, automation and online shopping could reduce demands for shopping malls, and retail property, which in the United States is currently estimated to account for 31% of all commercial property or around 7 billion square feet (650 million square metres).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Amazon has gained much of the growth in recent years for online shopping, accounting for half of the growth in online retail in 2016.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Other forms of automation can also be an integral part of online shopping, for example, the deployment of automated warehouse robotics such as that applied by Amazon using Kiva Systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The food retail industry has started to apply automation to the ordering process; McDonald's has introduced touch screen ordering and payment systems in many of its restaurants, reducing the need for as many cashier employees.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The University of Texas at Austin has introduced fully automated cafe retail locations.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Some cafes and restaurants have utilized mobile and tablet "apps" to make the ordering process more efficient by customers ordering and paying on their device.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Some restaurants have automated food delivery to tables of customers using a conveyor belt system.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The use of robots is sometimes employed to replace waiting staff.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automation in construction is the combination of methods, processes, and systems that allow for greater machine autonomy in construction activities.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Construction automation may have multiple goals, including but not limited to, reducing jobsite injuries, decreasing activity completion times, and assisting with quality control and quality assurance.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automated mining involves the removal of human labor from the mining process.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The mining industry is currently in the transition towards automation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Currently, it can still require a large amount of human capital, particularly in the third world where labor costs are low so there is less incentive for increasing efficiency through automation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) started the research and development of automated visual surveillance and monitoring (VSAM) program, between 1997 and 1999, and airborne video surveillance (AVS) programs, from 1998 to 2002.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Currently, there is a major effort underway in the vision community to develop a fully-automated tracking surveillance system.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automated video surveillance monitors people and vehicles in real-time within a busy environment.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Existing automated surveillance systems are based on the environment they are primarily designed to observe, i.e., indoor, outdoor or airborne, the number of sensors that the automated system can handle and the mobility of sensors, i.e., stationary camera vs. mobile camera.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The purpose of a surveillance system is to record properties and trajectories of objects in a given area, generate warnings or notify the designated authorities in case of occurrence of particular events.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] As demands for safety and mobility have grown and technological possibilities have multiplied, interest in automation has grown.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Seeking to accelerate the development and introduction of fully automated vehicles and highways, the U.S.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Congress authorized more than $650 million over six years for intelligent transport systems (ITS) and demonstration projects in the 1991 *Intermodal Surface Transportation Efficiency Act* (ISTEA).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Full automation commonly defined as requiring no control or very limited control by the driver; such automation would be accomplished through a combination of sensor, computer, and communications systems in vehicles and along the roadway.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Fully automated driving would, in theory, allow closer vehicle spacing and higher speeds, which could enhance traffic capacity in places where additional road building is physically impossible, politically unacceptable, or prohibitively expensive.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automated controls also might enhance road safety by reducing the opportunity for driver error, which causes a large share of motor vehicle crashes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Other potential benefits include improved air quality (as a result of more-efficient traffic flows), increased fuel economy, and spin-off technologies generated during research and development related to automated highway systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automated waste collection trucks prevent the need for as many workers as well as easing the level of labor required to provide the service.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Business process automation (BPA) is the technology-enabled automation of complex business processes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] It can help to streamline a business for simplicity, achieve digital transformation, increase service quality, improve service delivery or contain costs.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] BPA consists of integrating applications, restructuring labor resources and using software applications throughout the organization.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Robotic process automation (RPA; or RPAAI for self-guided RPA 2.0) is an emerging field within BPA and uses AI.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] BPAs can be implemented in a number of business areas including recruitment, marketing, sales and workflow.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Home automation (also called **domotics**) designates an emerging practice of increased automation of household appliances and features in residential dwellings, particularly through electronic means that allow for things impracticable, overly expensive or simply not possible in recent past decades.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The rise in the usage of home automation solutions has taken a turn reflecting the increased dependency of people on such automation solutions.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] However, the increased comfort that gets added through these automation solutions is remarkable.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Automation is essential for many scientific and clinical applications.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Therefore, automation has been extensively employed in laboratories.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] From as early as 1980 fully automated laboratories have already been working.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] However, automation has not become widespread in laboratories due to its high cost.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] This may change with the ability of integrating low-cost devices with standard laboratory equipment.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Autosamplers are common devices used in laboratory automation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Logistics automation is the application of computer software or automated machinery to improve the efficiency of logistics operations.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Typically this refers to operations within a warehouse or distribution center, with broader tasks undertaken by supply chain engineering systems and enterprise resource planning systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Industrial automation deals primarily with the automation of manufacturing, quality control, and material handling processes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] General-purpose controllers for industrial processes include programmable logic controllers, stand-alone I/O modules, and computers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Industrial automation is to replace the human action and manual command-response activities with the use of mechanized equipment and logical programming commands.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] One trend is increased use of machine vision to provide automatic inspection and robot guidance functions, another is a continuing increase in the use of robots.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Industrial automation is simply required in industries.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The rise of industrial automation is directly tied to the "Fourth Industrial Revolution", which is better known now as Industry 4.0.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Originating from Germany, Industry 4.0 encompasses numerous devices, concepts, and machines, as well as the advancement of the industrial internet of things (IIoT).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] An "Internet of Things is a seamless integration of diverse physical objects in the Internet through a virtual representation".
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] These new advancements have drawn attention to the world of automation and have shown ways for it to increase productivity and efficiency in machinery and manufacturing facilities.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 works with the IIoT and software/hardware to connect in a way that (through communication technologies) add enhancements and improve manufacturing processes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Being able to create more advanced manufacturing is now possible with these new technologies.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] It opens up an improved manufacturing platform.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Implementation of systems such as SCADA is an example of software that takes place in industrial automation today.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] SCADA is a supervisory data collection software, just one of the many used in industrial automation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Industry 4.0 covers many areas in manufacturing.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Industrial robotics is a sub-branch in industrial automation that aids in various manufacturing processes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Such manufacturing processes include machining, welding, painting, assembling and material handling to name a few.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Industrial robots use various mechanical, electrical as well as software systems to allow for high precision, accuracy and speed that far exceed any human performance.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The birth of industrial robots came shortly after World War II as the U.S. saw the need for a quicker way to produce industrial and consumer goods.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Servos, digital logic and solid-state electronics allowed engineers to build better and faster systems and over time these systems were improved and revised to the point where a single robot is capable of running 24 hours a day with little or no maintenance.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] In 1997, there were 700,000 industrial robots in use, the number has risen to 1.8M in 2017 In recent years, AI with robotics is also used in creating an automatic labeling solution, using robotic arms as the automatic label applicator, and AI for learning and detecting the products to be labelled.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Industrial automation incorporates programmable logic controllers in the manufacturing process.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) use a processing system which allows for variation of controls of inputs and outputs using simple programming.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] PLCs make use of programmable memory, storing instructions and functions like logic, sequencing, timing, counting, etc.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Using a logic-based language, a PLC can receive a variety of inputs and return a variety of logical outputs, the input devices being sensors and output devices being motors, valves, etc.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] PLCs are similar to computers, however, while computers are optimized for calculations, PLCs are optimized for control tasks and use in industrial environments.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] They are built so that only basic logic-based programming knowledge is needed and to handle vibrations, high temperatures, humidity, and noise.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The greatest advantage PLCs offer is their flexibility.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] With the same basic controllers, a PLC can operate a range of different control systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] PLCs make it unnecessary to rewire a system to change the control system.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] This flexibility leads to a cost-effective system for complex and varied control systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] PLCs can range from small "building brick" devices with tens of I/O in a housing integral with the processor, to large rack-mounted modular devices with a count of thousands of I/O, and which are often networked to other PLC and SCADA systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] They can be designed for multiple arrangements of digital and analog inputs and outputs (I/O), extended temperature ranges, immunity to electrical noise, and resistance to vibration and impact.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Programs to control machine operation are typically stored in battery-backed-up or non-volatile memory.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] It was from the automotive industry in the United States that the PLC was born.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Before the PLC, control, sequencing, and safety interlock logic for manufacturing automobiles was mainly composed of relays, cam timers, drum sequencers, and dedicated closed-loop controllers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Since these could number in the hundreds or even thousands, the process for updating such facilities for the yearly model change-over was very time-consuming and expensive, as electricians needed to individually rewire the relays to change their operational characteristics.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] When digital computers became available, being general-purpose programmable devices, they were soon applied to control sequential and combinatorial logic in industrial processes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] However, these early computers required specialist programmers and stringent operating environmental control for temperature, cleanliness, and power quality.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] To meet these challenges, the PLC was developed with several key attributes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] It would tolerate the shop-floor environment, it would support discrete (bit-form) input and output in an easily extensible manner, it would not require years of training to use, and it would permit its operation to be monitored.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Since many industrial processes have timescales easily addressed by millisecond response times, modern (fast, small, reliable) electronics greatly facilitate building reliable controllers, and performance could be traded off for reliability.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Agent-assisted automation refers to automation used by call center agents to handle customer inquiries.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The key benefit of agent-assisted automation is compliance and error-proofing.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] Agents are sometimes not fully trained or they forget or ignore key steps in the process.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] The use of automation ensures that what is supposed to happen on the call actually does, every time.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p01] There are two basic types: desktop automation and automated voice solutions.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Fundamentally, there are two types of control loop: *open-loop control* (feedforward), and *closed-loop control* (feedback).
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] One of the simplest types of control is *on-off* control.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] An example is a thermostat used on household appliances which either open or close an electrical contact.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Sequence control, in which a programmed sequence of *discrete* operations is performed, often based on system logic that involves system states.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] An elevator control system is an example of sequence control.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] A proportional–integral–derivative controller (PID controller) is a control loop feedback mechanism (controller) widely used in industrial control systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] The theoretical understanding and application date from the 1920s, and they are implemented in nearly all analog control systems; originally in mechanical controllers, and then using discrete electronics and latterly in industrial process computers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Sequential control may be either to a fixed sequence or to a logical one that will perform different actions depending on various system states.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] An example of an adjustable but otherwise fixed sequence is a timer on a lawn sprinkler.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] States refer to the various conditions that can occur in a use or sequence scenario of the system.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] An example is an elevator, which uses logic based on the system state to perform certain actions in response to its state and operator input.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] For example, if the operator presses the floor n button, the system will respond depending on whether the elevator is stopped or moving, going up or down, or if the door is open or closed, and other conditions.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Early development of sequential control was relay logic, by which electrical relays engage electrical contacts which either start or interrupt power to a device.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Relays were first used in telegraph networks before being developed for controlling other devices, such as when starting and stopping industrial-sized electric motors or opening and closing solenoid valves.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Using relays for control purposes allowed event-driven control, where actions could be triggered out of sequence, in response to external events.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] These were more flexible in their response than the rigid single-sequence cam timers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] More complicated examples involved maintaining safe sequences for devices such as swing bridge controls, where a lock bolt needed to be disengaged before the bridge could be moved, and the lock bolt could not be released until the safety gates had already been closed.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] The total number of relays and cam timers can number into the hundreds or even thousands in some factories.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Early programming techniques and languages were needed to make such systems manageable, one of the first being ladder logic, where diagrams of the interconnected relays resembled the rungs of a ladder.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Special computers called programmable logic controllers were later designed to replace these collections of hardware with a single, more easily re-programmed unit.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] In a typical hard-wired motor start and stop circuit (called a *control circuit*) a motor is started by pushing a "Start" or "Run" button that activates a pair of electrical relays.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] The "lock-in" relay locks in contacts that keep the control circuit energized when the push-button is released.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] (The start button is a normally open contact and the stop button is a normally closed contact.) Another relay energizes a switch that powers the device that throws the motor starter switch (three sets of contacts for three-phase industrial power) in the main power circuit.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Large motors use high voltage and experience high in-rush current, making speed important in making and breaking contact.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] This can be dangerous for personnel and property with manual switches.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] The "lock-in" contacts in the start circuit and the main power contacts for the motor are held engaged by their respective electromagnets until a "stop" or "off" button is pressed, which de-energizes the lock in relay.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Commonly interlocks are added to a control circuit.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Suppose that the motor in the example is powering machinery that has a critical need for lubrication.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] In this case, an interlock could be added to ensure that the oil pump is running before the motor starts.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Timers, limit switches, and electric eyes are other common elements in control circuits.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Solenoid valves are widely used on compressed air or hydraulic fluid for powering actuators on mechanical components.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Computers can perform both sequential control and feedback control, and typically a single computer will do both in an industrial application.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Programmable logic controllers (PLCs) are a type of special-purpose microprocessor that replaced many hardware components such as timers and drum sequencers used in relay logic–type systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] General-purpose process control computers have increasingly replaced stand-alone controllers, with a single computer able to perform the operations of hundreds of controllers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Process control computers can process data from a network of PLCs, instruments, and controllers to implement typical (such as PID) control of many individual variables or, in some cases, to implement complex control algorithms using multiple inputs and mathematical manipulations.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] They can also analyze data and create real-time graphical displays for operators and run reports for operators, engineers, and management.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Control of an automated teller machine (ATM) is an example of an interactive process in which a computer will perform a logic-derived response to a user selection based on information retrieved from a networked database.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] The ATM process has similarities with other online transaction processes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] The different logical responses are called *scenarios*.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] Such processes are typically designed with the aid of use cases and flowcharts, which guide the writing of the software code.
[src:kubernetes-operators/automation-p02] The earliest feedback control mechanism was the water clock invented by Greek engineer Ctesibius (285–222 BC).
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] A **control loop** is the fundamental building block of control systems in general and industrial control systems in particular.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] It consists of the process sensor, the controller function, and the final control element (FCE) which controls the process necessary to automatically adjust the value of a measured process variable (PV) to equal the value of a desired set-point (SP).
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] There are two common classes of control loop: open loop and closed loop.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] An example of a control system is a car's cruise control, which is a device designed to maintain vehicle speed at a constant *desired* or *reference* speed provided by the driver.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] The *controller* is the cruise control, the *plant* is the car, and the *system* is the car and the cruise control.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] The system output is the car's speed, and the control itself is the engine's throttle position which determines how much power the engine delivers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] A primitive way to implement cruise control is simply to lock the throttle position when the driver engages cruise control.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] However, if the cruise control is engaged on a stretch of non-flat road, then the car will travel slower going uphill and faster when going downhill.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] In a *closed-loop control system*, data from a sensor monitoring the car's speed (the system output) enters a controller which continuously compares the quantity representing the speed with the reference quantity representing the desired speed.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] The difference, called the error, determines the throttle position (the control).
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] The result is to match the car's speed to the reference speed (maintain the desired system output).
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] Now, when the car goes uphill, the difference between the input (the sensed speed) and the reference continuously determines the throttle position.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] As the sensed speed drops below the reference, the difference increases, the throttle opens, and engine power increases, speeding up the vehicle.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] In this way, the controller dynamically counteracts changes to the car's speed.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] The central idea of these control systems is the *feedback loop*, the controller affects the system output, which in turn is measured and fed back to the controller.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] The accompanying diagram shows a control loop with a single PV input, a control function, and the control output (CO) which modulates the action of the final control element (FCE) to alter the value of the manipulated variable (MV).
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] In this example, a flow control loop is shown, but can be level, temperature, or any one of many process parameters which need to be controlled.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] The control function shown is an "intermediate type" such as a PID controller which means it can generate a full range of output signals anywhere between 0-100%, rather than just an on/off signal.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] In this example, the value of the PV is always the same as the MV, as they are in series in the pipeline.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] However, if the feed from the valve was to a tank, and the controller function was to control the level using the fill valve, the PV would be the tank level, and the MV would be the flow to the tank.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] The controller function can be a discrete controller or a function block in a computerised control system such as a distributed control system or a programmable logic controller.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] In all cases, a control loop diagram is a very convenient and useful way of representing the control function and its interaction with plant.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] In practice at a process control level, control loops are normally abbreviated using standard symbols in a Piping and instrumentation diagram, which shows all elements of the process measurement and control based on a process flow diagram.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] At a detailed level, the control loop connection diagram is created to show the electrical and pneumatic connections.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] This greatly aids diagnostics and repair, as all the connections for a single control function are on one diagram.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] To aid unique identification of equipment, each loop and its elements are identified by a "tagging" system and each element has a unique tag identification.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] Based on the standards ANSI/ISA S5.1 and ISO 14617-6, the identifications consist of up to 5 letters.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] The first identification letter is for the measured value, the second is a modifier, 3rd indicates the passive/readout function, 4th - active/output function, and the 5th is the function modifier.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] This is followed by loop number, which is unique to that loop.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] For instance, FIC045 means it is the Flow Indicating Controller in control loop 045.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] This is also known as the "tag" identifier of the field device, which is normally given to the location and function of the instrument.
[src:kubernetes-operators/control-loop] The same loop may have FT045 - which is the flow transmitter in the same loop.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] In computer science, **declarative programming** is a programming paradigm that expresses the logic of a computation without fully describing its control flow.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] This is in contrast with imperative programming, which implements algorithms in explicit steps.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Declarative programming may consider programs as theories of a formal logic, and computations as deductions in that logical theory.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Declarative programming at times simplifies the writing of parallel programs.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Common declarative language paradigms include logic programming (e.g., Prolog, Datalog, answer set programming), and algebraic modeling systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is often defined as any style of programming that is not imperative.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] A number of other common definitions attempt to define it by simply contrasting it with imperative programming.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] These definitions overlap substantially.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is a non-imperative style of programming in which programs describe their desired results without explicitly listing commands or steps that must be performed.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages are characterized by a mostly declarative programming style.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] In logic programming, programs consist of sentences expressed in logical form, and computation uses those sentences to solve problems, which are also expressed in logical form.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] In a pure functional language, such as Haskell, all functions are without side effects, and state changes are only represented as functions that transform the state, which is explicitly represented as a first-class object in the program.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Although pure functional languages are non-imperative, they often provide a facility for describing the effect of a function as a series of steps.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Other functional languages, such as Lisp, OCaml and Erlang, support a mixture of procedural and functional programming.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Some logic programming languages, such as Prolog, and database query languages, such as SQL, while declarative in principle, also support a procedural style of programming.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Declarative programming is an umbrella term that includes a number of better-known programming paradigms.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Constraint programming states relations between variables in the form of constraints that specify the properties of the target solution.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] The set of constraints is solved by giving a value to each variable so that the solution is consistent with the maximum number of constraints.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Constraint programming often complements other paradigms: functional, logical, or even imperative programming.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Makefiles, for example, specify dependencies in a declarative fashion, but include an imperative list of actions to take as well.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Similarly, yacc specifies a context free grammar declaratively, but includes code snippets from a host language, which is usually imperative (such as C).
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Logic programming languages, such as Prolog, Datalog and answer set programming, compute by proving that a goal is a logical consequence of the program, or by showing that the goal is true in a model defined by the program.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Prolog computes by reducing goals to subgoals, top-down using backward reasoning, whereas most Datalog systems compute bottom-up using forward reasoning.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Answer set programs typically use SAT solvers to generate a model of the program.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Models, or mathematical representations, of physical systems may be implemented in computer code that is declarative.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] The code contains a number of equations, not imperative assignments, that describe ("declare") the behavioral relationships.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] When a model is expressed in this formalism, a computer is able to perform algebraic manipulations to best formulate the solution algorithm.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] The mathematical causality is typically imposed at the boundaries of the physical system, while the behavioral description of the system itself is declarative or acausal.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Declarative modeling languages and environments include Analytica, Modelica and Simile.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Prolog (1972) stands for "PROgramming in LOGic." It was developed for natural language question answering, using SL resolution both to deduce answers to queries and to parse and generate natural language sentences.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] The building blocks of a Prolog program are *facts* and *rules*.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Given this program, the query `eat(tom,jerry)` succeeds, while `eat(jerry,tom)` fails.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Moreover, the query `eat(X,jerry)` succeeds with the answer substitution `X=tom`.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Prolog executes programs top-down, using SLD resolution to reason backwards, reducing goals to subgoals.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] In this example, it uses the last rule of the program to reduce the goal of answering the query `eat(X,jerry)` to the subgoals of first finding an X such that `big(X)` holds and then of showing that `small(jerry)` holds.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] It repeatedly uses rules to further reduce subgoals to other subgoals, until it eventually succeeds in unifying all subgoals with facts in the program.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] This backward reasoning, goal-reduction strategy treats rules in logic programs as procedures, and makes Prolog both a declarative and procedural programming language.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] The broad range of Prolog applications is highlighted in the Year of Prolog Book, celebrating the 50 year anniversary of Prolog.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] The origins of Datalog date back to the beginning of logic programming, but it was identified as a separate area around 1977.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Syntactically and semantically, it is a subset of Prolog.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] But because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Most Datalog systems execute programs bottom-up, using rules to reason forwards, deriving new facts from existing facts, and terminating when there are no new facts that can be derived, or when the derived facts unify with the query.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Datalog has been applied to such problems as data integration, information extraction, networking, security, cloud computing and machine learning.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Answer set programming (ASP) evolved in the late 1990s, based on the stable model (answer set) semantics of logic programming.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Like Datalog, it is a subset of Prolog; and, because it lacks compound terms, it is not Turing-complete.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Most implementations of ASP execute a program by first *grounding* the program, replacing all variables in rules by constants in all possible ways, and then using a propositional SAT solver, such as the DPLL algorithm to generate one or more models of the program.
[src:kubernetes-operators/declarative-programming] Its applications are oriented towards solving difficult search problems and knowledge representation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] Operators are software extensions to Kubernetes that make use of custom resources to manage applications and their components.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] Operators follow Kubernetes principles, notably the control loop.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] The *operator pattern* aims to capture the key aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] Human operators who look after specific applications and services have deep knowledge of how the system ought to behave, how to deploy it, and how to react if there are problems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] People who run workloads on Kubernetes often like to use automation to take care of repeatable tasks.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] The operator pattern captures how you can write code to automate a task beyond what Kubernetes itself provides.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] Out of the box, you get lots of built-in automation from the core of Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] You can use Kubernetes to automate deploying and running workloads, *and* you can automate how Kubernetes does that.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] Kubernetes' operator pattern concept lets you extend the cluster's behaviour without modifying the code of Kubernetes itself by linking controllers to one or more custom resources.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] Operators are clients of the Kubernetes API that act as controllers for a Custom Resource.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] What might an operator look like in more detail?
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] A Deployment that makes sure a Pod is running that contains the controller part of the operator.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] Controller code that queries the control plane to find out what SampleDB resources are configured.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] The core of the operator is code to tell the API server how to make reality match the configured resources.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] The operator also manages regular database backups.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] For each SampleDB resource, the operator determines when to create a Pod that can connect to the database and take backups.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] These Pods would rely on a ConfigMap and / or a Secret that has database connection details and credentials.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] Because the operator aims to provide robust automation for the resource it manages, there would be additional supporting code.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] For this example, code checks to see if the database is running an old version and, if so, creates Job objects that upgrade it for you.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] The most common way to deploy an operator is to add the Custom Resource Definition and its associated Controller to your cluster.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] The Controller will normally run outside of the control plane, much as you would run any containerized application.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] For example, you can run the controller in your cluster as a Deployment.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] Once you have an operator deployed, you'd use it by adding, modifying or deleting the kind of resource that the operator uses.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] The operator will take care of applying the changes as well as keeping the existing service in good shape.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] If there isn't an operator in the ecosystem that implements the behavior you want, you can code your own.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] You also implement an operator (that is, a Controller) using any language / runtime that can act as a client for the Kubernetes API.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] Following are a few libraries and tools you can use to write your own cloud native operator.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] This section links to third party projects that provide functionality required by Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] The Kubernetes project authors aren't responsible for these projects, which are listed alphabetically.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] Items on this page refer to third party products or projects that provide functionality required by Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] The Kubernetes project authors aren't responsible for those third-party products or projects.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] See the CNCF website guidelines for more details.
[src:kubernetes-operators/extend-kubernetes-operator] You should read the content guide before proposing a change that adds an extra third-party link.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The name *Kubernetes* comes from the Ancient Greek term κυβερνήτης, *kubernḗtēs* (helmsman, pilot), which is also the origin of the words *cybernetics* and (through Latin) *governor*.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] "Kubernetes" is often abbreviated with the numerical contraction "K8s", meaning "the letter K, followed by 8 letters, followed by s".
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes assembles one or more computers, either virtual machines or bare metal, into a cluster which can run workloads in containers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] It works with various container runtimes, such as containerd and CRI-O.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Its suitability for running and managing workloads of all sizes and styles has led to its widespread adoption in clouds and data centers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] There are multiple distributions of this platform—from independent software vendors (ISVs) as well as hosted-on-cloud offerings from all the major public cloud vendors.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The software consists of a control plane and nodes on which the actual applications run.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] It includes tools like `kubeadm` and `kubectl` which can be used to interact with its REST-based API.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced by Google on June 6, 2014.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The project was conceived and created by Google employees Joe Beda, Brendan Burns, and Craig McLuckie.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Others at Google soon joined to help build the project including Ville Aikas, Dawn Chen, Brian Grant, Tim Hockin, and Daniel Smith.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Other companies such as Red Hat and CoreOS joined the effort soon after, with notable contributors such as Clayton Coleman and Kelsey Hightower.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The design and development of Kubernetes was inspired by Google's Borg cluster manager and based on Promise Theory.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Many of its top contributors had previously worked on Borg; they codenamed Kubernetes "Project 7" after the *Star Trek* ex-Borg character Seven of Nine and gave its logo a seven-spoked ship's wheel (designed by Tim Hockin).
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Unlike Borg, which was written in C++, Kubernetes is written in the Go language.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes was announced in June, 2014 and version 1.0 was released on July 21, 2015.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Google worked with the Linux Foundation to form the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF) and offered Kubernetes as the seed technology.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Google was already offering a managed Kubernetes service, GKE, and Red Hat was supporting Kubernetes as part of OpenShift since the inception of the Kubernetes project in 2014.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] On March 6, 2018, Kubernetes Project reached ninth place in the list of GitHub projects by the number of commits, and second place in authors and issues, after the Linux kernel.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Until version 1.18, Kubernetes followed an N-2 support policy, meaning that the three most recent minor versions receive security updates and bug fixes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Starting with version 1.19, Kubernetes follows an N-3 support policy.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines a set of building blocks ("primitives") that collectively provide mechanisms that deploy, maintain, and scale applications based on CPU, memory or custom metrics.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes is loosely coupled and extensible to meet the needs of different workloads.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The internal components as well as extensions and containers that run on Kubernetes rely on the Kubernetes API.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The platform exerts its control over compute and storage resources by defining resources as objects, which can then be managed as such.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes follows the primary/replica architecture.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The components of Kubernetes can be divided into those that manage an individual node and those that are part of the control plane.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The Kubernetes master node handles the Kubernetes control plane of the cluster, managing its workload and directing communication across the system.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The Kubernetes control plane consists of various components such as TLS encryption, role-based access control (RBAC) and a strong authentication method, network separation, each its own process, that can run both on a single master node or on multiple masters supporting high-availability clusters.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The various components of the Kubernetes control plane are as follows.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Etcd is a persistent, lightweight, distributed, key-value data store (originally developed as part of CoreOS).
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] It reliably stores the configuration data of the cluster, representing the overall state of the cluster at any given point of time.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Etcd favors consistency over availability in the event of a network partition (see CAP theorem).
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The consistency is crucial for correctly scheduling and operating services.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The API server serves the Kubernetes API using JSON over HTTP, which provides both the internal and external interface to Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The API server processes, validates REST requests, and updates the state of the API objects in etcd, thereby allowing clients to configure workloads and containers across worker nodes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The API server uses etcd's watch API to monitor the cluster, roll out critical configuration changes, or restore any divergences of the state of the cluster back to the desired state as declared in etcd.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] As an example, a human operator may specify that three instances of a particular "pod" (see below) need to be running, and etcd stores this fact.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] If the Deployment controller finds that only two instances are running (conflicting with the etcd declaration), it schedules the creation of an additional instance of that pod.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The scheduler is an extensible component that selects the node that an unscheduled pod (the basic unit of workloads to be scheduled) runs on, based on resource availability and other constraints.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The scheduler tracks resource allocation on each node to ensure that workload is not scheduled in excess of available resources.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] For this purpose, the scheduler must know the resource requirements, resource availability, and other user-provided constraints or policy directives such as quality-of-service, affinity/anti-affinity requirements, and data locality.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The scheduler's role is to match resource "supply" to workload "demand".
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes allows running multiple schedulers within a single cluster.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] As such, scheduler plug-ins may be developed and installed as in-process extensions to the native vanilla scheduler by running it as a separate scheduler, as long as they conform to the Kubernetes scheduling framework.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] This allows cluster administrators to extend or modify the behavior of the default Kubernetes scheduler according to their needs.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A controller is a reconciliation loop that drives the actual cluster state toward the desired state, communicating with the API server to create, update, and delete the resources it manages (e.g., pods or service endpoints).
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] An example controller is a ReplicaSet controller, which handles replication and scaling by running a specified number of copies of a pod across the cluster.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The controller also handles creating replacement pods if the underlying node fails.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Other controllers that are part of the core Kubernetes system include a DaemonSet controller for running exactly one pod on every machine (or some subset of machines), and a Job controller for running pods that run to completion (e.g. as part of a batch job).
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Labels selectors often form part of the controller's definition that specify the set of pods that a controller manages.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The controller manager is a single process that manages several core Kubernetes controllers (including the examples described above), is distributed as part of the standard Kubernetes installation and responding to the loss of nodes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Custom controllers may also be installed in the cluster, further allowing the behavior and API of Kubernetes to be extended when used in conjunction with custom resources (see custom resources, controllers and operators below).
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A node, also known as a worker or a minion, is a machine where containers (workloads) are deployed.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Every node in the cluster must run a container runtime, as well as the below-mentioned components, for communication with the primary network configuration of these containers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] kubelet is responsible for the running state of each node, ensuring that all containers on the node are healthy.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] It takes care of starting, stopping, and maintaining application containers organized into pods as directed by the control plane. kubelet monitors the state of a pod, and if not in the desired state, the pod re-deploys to the same node.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Node status is relayed every few seconds via heartbeat messages to the API server.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Once the control plane detects a node failure, a higher-level controller is expected to observe this state change and launch pods on another healthy node.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A container runtime is responsible for the lifecycle of containers, including launching, reconciling and killing of containers. kubelet interacts with container runtimes via the Container Runtime Interface (CRI), which decouples the maintenance of core Kubernetes from the actual CRI implementation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Originally, kubelet interfaced exclusively with the Docker runtime through a "dockershim".
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] However, from November 2020 up to April 2022, Kubernetes has deprecated the shim in favor of directly interfacing with the container through containerd, or replacing Docker with a runtime that is compliant with the Container Runtime Interface (CRI).
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] With the release of v1.24 in May 2022, the "dockershim" has been removed entirely.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Examples of popular container runtimes that are compatible with kubelet include containerd (initially supported via Docker) and CRI-O.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] kube-proxy is an implementation of a network proxy and a load balancer, and it supports the service abstraction along with the other networking operations.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] It is responsible for routing traffic to the appropriate container based on IP and port number of the incoming request.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, namespaces are utilized to segregate the resources it handles into distinct and non-intersecting collections.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] They are intended for use in environments with many users spread across multiple teams, or projects, or even separating environments like development, test, and production.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The basic scheduling unit in Kubernetes is a pod, which consists of one or more containers that are guaranteed to be co-located on the same node.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Each pod in Kubernetes is assigned a unique IP address within the cluster, allowing applications to use ports without the risk of conflict.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Within the pod, all containers can reference each other.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The container is the lowest level of a micro-service, which holds the running application, libraries, and their dependencies.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes supports several abstractions of workloads that are at a higher level over simple pods.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] This allows users to declaratively define and manage these high-level abstractions, instead of having to manage individual pods by themselves.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Several of these abstractions, supported by a standard installation of Kubernetes, are described below.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A ReplicaSet's purpose is to maintain a stable set of replica pods running at any given time.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] As such, it is often used to guarantee the availability of a specified number of identical Pods.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The ReplicaSet can also be said to be a grouping mechanism that lets Kubernetes maintain the number of instances that have been declared for a given pod.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The definition of a ReplicaSet uses a selector, whose evaluation will result in identifying all pods that are associated with it.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A ReplicationController, similar to a ReplicaSet, serves the same purpose and behaves similarly to a ReplicaSet, which is to ensure that there will always be a specified number of pod replicas as desired.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The ReplicationController workload was the predecessor of a ReplicaSet, but was eventually deprecated in favor of ReplicaSet to make use of set-based label selectors.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Deployments are a higher-level management mechanism for ReplicaSets.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] While the ReplicaSet controller manages the scale of the ReplicaSet, the Deployment controller manages what happens to the ReplicaSet – whether an update has to be rolled out, or rolled back, etc.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] When Deployments are scaled up or down, this results in the declaration of the ReplicaSet changing, and this change in the declared state is managed by the ReplicaSet controller.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] StatefulSets are controllers that enforce the properties of uniqueness and ordering amongst instances of a pod, and can be used to run stateful applications.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] While scaling stateless applications is only a matter of adding more running pods, doing so for stateful workloads is harder, because the state needs to be preserved if a pod is restarted.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] If the application is scaled up or down, the state may need to be redistributed.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Databases are an example of stateful workloads.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] When run in high-availability mode, many databases come with the notion of a primary instance and secondary instances.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of ordering of instances is important.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Other applications like Apache Kafka distribute the data amongst their brokers; hence, one broker is not the same as another.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] In this case, the notion of instance uniqueness is important.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] DaemonSets are responsible for ensuring that a pod is created on every single node in the cluster.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Generally, most workloads scale in response to a desired replica count, depending on the availability and performance requirements as needed by the application.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] However, in other scenarios it may be necessary to deploy a pod to every single node in the cluster, scaling up the number of total pods as nodes are added and garbage collecting them as they are removed.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] This is particularly helpful for use cases where the workload has some dependency on the actual node or host machine, such as log collection, ingress controllers, and storage services.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A Kubernetes service is a set of pods that work together, such as one tier of a multi-tier application.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The set of pods that constitute a service are defined by a label selector.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two modes of service discovery, using environment variables or using Kubernetes DNS.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Service discovery assigns a stable IP address and DNS name to the service, and load balances traffic in a round-robin manner to network connections of that IP address among the pods matching the selector (even as failures cause the pods to move from machine to machine).
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] By default a service is exposed inside a cluster (e.g., back end pods might be grouped into a service, with requests from the front-end pods load-balanced among them), but a service can also be exposed outside a cluster (e.g., for clients to reach front-end pods).
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Filesystems in the Kubernetes container provide ephemeral storage, by default.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] This means that a restart of the pod will wipe out any data on such containers, and therefore, this form of storage is quite limiting in anything but trivial applications.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A Kubernetes volume provides persistent storage that exists for the lifetime of the pod itself.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] This storage can also be used as shared disk space for containers within the pod.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Volumes are mounted at specific mount points within the container, which are defined by the pod configuration, and cannot mount onto other volumes or link to other volumes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The same volume can be mounted at different points in the file system tree by different containers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A common application challenge is deciding where to store and manage configuration information, some of which may contain sensitive data.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Configuration data can be anything as fine-grained as individual properties, or coarse-grained information like entire configuration files such as JSON or XML documents.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides two closely related mechanisms to deal with this need, known as ConfigMaps and Secrets, both of which allow for configuration changes to be made without requiring an application rebuild.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The data from ConfigMaps and Secrets will be made available to every single instance of the application to which these objects have been bound via the Deployment.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A Secret and/or a ConfigMap is sent to a node only if a pod on that node requires it, which will only be stored in memory on the node.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Once the pod that depends on the Secret or ConfigMap is deleted, the in-memory copy of all bound Secrets and ConfigMaps are deleted as well.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Mounted within a volume accessible within the container's filesystem, which supports automatic reloading without restarting the container.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The biggest difference between a Secret and a ConfigMap is that Secrets are specifically designed for containing secure and confidential data, although they are not encrypted at rest by default, and requires additional setup in order to fully secure the use of Secrets within the cluster.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Secrets are often used to store confidential or sensitive data like certificates, credentials to work with image registries, passwords, and ssh keys.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes enables clients (users or internal components) to attach keys called labels to any API object in the system, such as pods and nodes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Correspondingly, label selectors are queries against labels that resolve to matching objects.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] When a service is defined, one can define the label selectors that will be used by the service router/load balancer to select the pod instances that the traffic will be routed to.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Thus, simply changing the labels of the pods or changing the label selectors on the service can be used to control which pods get traffic and which don't, which can be used to support various deployment patterns like blue–green deployments or A/B testing.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] This capability to dynamically control how services utilize implementing resources provides a loose coupling within the infrastructure.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Just like labels, field selectors also let one select Kubernetes resources.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Unlike labels, the selection is based on the attribute values inherent to the resource being selected, rather than user-defined categorization.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] `metadata.name` and `metadata.namespace` are field selectors that will be present on all Kubernetes objects.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Other selectors that can be used depend on the object/resource type.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Add-ons are additional features of the Kubernetes cluster implemented as applications running within it.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The pods may be managed by Deployments, ReplicationControllers, and so on.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Cluster DNS is a DNS server, in addition to the other DNS server(s) in the environment, which serves DNS records for Kubernetes services.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Containers started by Kubernetes automatically include this DNS server in their DNS searches.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] This is a general purpose, web-based UI for Kubernetes clusters.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] It allows administrators to manage and troubleshoot applications running in the cluster, as well as the cluster itself.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Container Resource Monitoring records metrics about containers in a central database, and provides a UI for browsing that data.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes cost monitoring applications allow breakdown of costs by pods, nodes, namespaces, and labels.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] To prevent the loss of event data in the event of node or pod failures, container logs can be saved to a central log store with a search/browsing interface.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes provides no native storage for log data, but one can integrate many existing logging solutions into the Kubernetes cluster.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Containers emerged as a way to make software portable.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The container contains all the packages needed to run a service.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The provided file system makes containers extremely portable and easy to use in development.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A container can be moved from development to test or production with no or relatively few configuration changes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Historically Kubernetes was suitable only for stateless services.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] However, many applications have a database, which requires persistence, leading to the creation of persistent storage for Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Implementing persistent storage for containers is one of the top challenges of Kubernetes administrators, DevOps and cloud engineers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Containers may be ephemeral, but more and more of their data is not, so one needs to ensure the data's survival in case of container termination or hardware failure.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] When deploying containers with Kubernetes or containerized applications, organizations often realize that they need persistent storage.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] They need to provide fast and reliable storage for databases, root images and other data used by the containers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] In addition to the landscape, the Cloud Native Computing Foundation (CNCF), has published other information about Kubernetes Persistent Storage including a blog helping to define the container attached storage pattern.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] This pattern can be thought of as one that uses Kubernetes itself as a component of the storage system or service.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Container Attached Storage is a type of data storage that emerged as Kubernetes gained prominence.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The Container Attached Storage approach or pattern relies on Kubernetes itself for certain capabilities while delivering primarily block, file, object and interfaces to workloads running on Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Common attributes of Container Attached Storage include the use of extensions to Kubernetes, such as custom resource definitions, and the use of Kubernetes itself for functions that otherwise would be separately developed and deployed for storage or data management.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Examples of functionality delivered by custom resource definitions or by Kubernetes itself include retry logic, delivered by Kubernetes itself, and the creation and maintenance of an inventory of available storage media and volumes, typically delivered via a custom resource definition.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] In Kubernetes version 1.9, the initial Alpha release of Container Storage Interface (CSI) was introduced.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Previously, storage volume plug-ins were included in the Kubernetes distribution.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] By creating a standardized CSI, the code required to interface with external storage systems was separated from the core Kubernetes code base.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Just one year later, the CSI feature was made Generally Available (GA) in Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A key component of the Kubernetes control plane is the API Server, which exposes an HTTP API that can be invoked by other parts of the cluster as well as end users and external components.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] This API is a REST API and is declarative in nature, and is the same API exposed to the control plane.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The API server is backed by etcd to store all records persistently.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] In Kubernetes, all objects serve as the "record of intent" of the cluster's state, and are able to define the desired state that the writer of the object wishes for the cluster to be in.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] All objects in Kubernetes are subject to the same API conventions.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API can be extended using *Custom Resources*, which represent objects that are not part of the standard Kubernetes installation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] These custom resources are declared using *Custom Resource Definitions* (CRDs), which is a kind of resource that can be dynamically registered and unregistered without shutting down or restarting a cluster that is currently running.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Custom controllers are another extension mechanism that interact with the Kubernetes API, similar to the default controllers in the standard pre-installed Kubernetes controller manager.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] These controllers may interact with custom resources to allow for a declarative API: users may declare the desired state of the system via the custom resources, and it is the responsibility of the custom controller to observe the change and reconcile it.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The combination of custom resources and custom controllers are often referred to as a *Kubernetes* *Operator*.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The key use case for operators are to capture the aim of a human operator who is managing a service or set of services and to implement them using automation, and with a declarative API supporting this automation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Examples of problems solved by operators include taking and restoring backups of that application's state, and handling upgrades of the application code alongside related changes such as database schemas or extra configuration settings.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Several notable projects under the Cloud Native Computing Foundation's incubation program follow the operator pattern to extend Kubernetes, including Argo, Open Policy Agent and Istio.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes defines the following strategies for controlling access to its API.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The Kubernetes API server listens on a TCP port that serves HTTPS traffic, in order to enforce transport layer security (TLS) using CA certificates.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] In older versions of Kubernetes, the API server supported listening on both HTTP and HTTPS ports (with the HTTP port number having no transport security whatsoever).
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] This was deprecated in v1.10 and eventually dropped support in v1.20 of Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Users are typically expected to indicate and define cluster URL details along with the necessary credentials in a *kubeconfig* file, which are natively supported by other Kubernetes tools like kubectl and the official Kubernetes client libraries.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] *Attribute-based access control (ABAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users through the use of defined access control policies which combine attributes together.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] *Role-based access control (RBAC) mode*: Grants access rights to users based on roles that are granted to the user, where each role defines a list of actions that are allowed.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] *Webhook mode*: Queries a REST API service to determine if a user is authorized to perform a given action.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The same API design principles have been used to define an API to harness a program in order to create, configure, and manage Kubernetes clusters.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A key concept embodied in the API is using Infrastructure as Software, or the notion that the Kubernetes cluster infrastructure is itself a resource / object that can be managed just like any other Kubernetes resources.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Similarly, machines that make up the cluster are also treated as a Kubernetes resource.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The API has two pieces – the core API, and a provider implementation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] The provider implementation consists of cloud-provider specific functions that let Kubernetes provide the cluster API in a fashion that is well-integrated with the cloud-provider's services and resources.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Kubernetes is commonly used as a way to host a microservice-based implementation, because it and its associated ecosystem of tools provide all the capabilities needed to address key concerns of any microservice architecture.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] A common criticism of Kubernetes is that it is too complex.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] Various vendors offer Kubernetes-based platforms or infrastructure as a service (IaaS) that deploy Kubernetes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/kubernetes] These are typically categorized according to open-source, commercial or managed distributions.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] In computer science, a **software agent** is a computer program that acts for a user or another program in a relationship of agency.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The term *agent* is derived from the Latin *agere* (to do): an agreement to act on one's behalf.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Such "action on behalf of" implies the authority to decide which, if any, action is appropriate.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Some agents are colloquially known as *bots*, from *robot*.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] They may be embodied, as when execution is paired with a robot body, or as software such as a chatbot executing on a computer, such as a mobile device, e.g.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Software agents may be autonomous or work together with other agents or people.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Software agents interacting with people (e.g. chatbots, human-robot interaction environments) may possess human-like qualities such as natural language understanding and speech, personality or embody humanoid form (see Asimo).
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The concept of an agent provides a method of describing a complex software entity that is capable of acting with a certain degree of autonomy in order to accomplish tasks on behalf of its host.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] But unlike objects, which are defined in terms of *methods* and *attributes*, an agent is defined in terms of its behavior.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] All agents are programs, but not all programs are agents.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Contrasting the term with related concepts may help clarify its meaning.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Franklin & Graesser (1997) discuss four key notions that distinguish agents from arbitrary programs: reaction to the environment, autonomy, goal-orientation and persistence.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Software agents may offer various benefits to their end users by automating complex or repetitive tasks.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] However, there are organizational and cultural impacts of this technology that need to be considered prior to implementing software agents.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] People like to perform easy tasks providing the sensation of success unless the repetition of the simple tasking is affecting the overall output.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] In general implementing software agents to perform administrative requirements provides a substantial increase in work contentment, as administering their own work does never please the worker.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The effort freed up serves for a higher degree of engagement in the substantial tasks of individual work.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Hence, software agents may provide the basics to implement self-controlled work, relieved from hierarchical controls and interference.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Such conditions may be secured by application of software agents for required formal support.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The cultural effects of the implementation of software agents include trust affliction, skills erosion, privacy attrition and social detachment.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Some users may not feel entirely comfortable fully delegating important tasks to software applications.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Those who start relying solely on intelligent agents may lose important skills, for example, relating to information literacy.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] In order to act on a user's behalf, a software agent needs to have a complete understanding of a user's profile, including his/her personal preferences.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] This, in turn, may lead to unpredictable privacy issues.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] When users start relying on their software agents more, especially for communication activities, they may lose contact with other human users and look at the world with the eyes of their agents.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] These consequences are what agent researchers and users must consider when dealing with intelligent agent technologies.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] To be more academic, software agent systems are a direct evolution of Multi-Agent Systems (MAS).
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] MAS evolved from Distributed Artificial Intelligence (DAI), Distributed Problem Solving (DPS) and Parallel AI (PAI), thus inheriting all characteristics (good and bad) from DAI and AI.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] John Sculley's 1987 "Knowledge Navigator" video portrayed an image of a relationship between end-users and agents.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Being an ideal first, this field experienced a series of unsuccessful top-down implementations, instead of a piece-by-piece, bottom-up approach.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The range of agent types is now (from 1990) broad: WWW, search engines, etc.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Buyer agents travel around a network (e.g. the internet) retrieving information about goods and services.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] These agents, also known as 'shopping bots', work very efficiently for commodity products such as CDs, books, electronic components, and other one-size-fits-all products.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Buyer agents are typically optimized to allow for digital payment services used in e-commerce and traditional businesses.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] User agents, or personal agents, are intelligent agents that take action on your behalf.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Monitoring and surveillance agents are used to observe and report on equipment, usually computer systems.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The agents may keep track of company inventory levels, observe competitors' prices and relay them back to the company, watch stock manipulation by insider trading and rumors, etc.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] For example, NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory has an agent that monitors inventory, planning, schedules equipment orders to keep costs down, and manages food storage facilities.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] These agents usually monitor complex computer networks that can keep track of the configuration of each computer connected to the network.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] A special case of monitoring-and-surveillance agents are organizations of agents used to automate decision-making process during tactical operations.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The agents monitor the status of assets (ammunition, weapons available, platforms for transport, etc.) and receive goals from higher level agents.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The agents then pursue the goals with the assets at hand, minimizing expenditure of the assets while maximizing goal attainment.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] This agent uses information technology to find trends and patterns in an abundance of information from many different sources.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The user can sort through this information in order to find whatever information they are seeking.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] A data mining agent operates in a data warehouse discovering information.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] A 'data warehouse' brings together information from many different sources.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] "Data mining" is the process of looking through the data warehouse to find information that you can use to take action, such as ways to increase sales or keep customers who are considering defecting.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] 'Classification' is one of the most common types of data mining, which finds patterns in information and categorizes them into different classes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Data mining agents can also detect major shifts in trends or a key indicator and can detect the presence of new information and alert you to it.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] For example, the agent may detect a decline in the construction industry for an economy; based on this relayed information construction companies will be able to make intelligent decisions regarding the hiring/firing of employees or the purchase/lease of equipment in order to best suit their firm.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Some other examples of current intelligent agents include some spam filters, game bots, and server monitoring tools.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Search engine indexing bots also qualify as intelligent agents.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Software bots are becoming important in software engineering.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Agents are also used in software security application to intercept, examine and act on various types of content.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] For software agents to work together efficiently they must share semantics of their data elements.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] This can be done by having computer systems publish their metadata.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Agent systems are used to model real-world systems with concurrency or parallel processing.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The agent uses its access methods to go out into local and remote databases to forage for content.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] These access methods may include setting up news stream delivery to the agent, or retrieval from bulletin boards, or using a spider to walk the Web.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The content that is retrieved in this way is probably already partially filtered – by the selection of the newsfeed or the databases that are searched.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The agent next may use its detailed searching or language-processing machinery to extract keywords or signatures from the body of the content that has been received or retrieved.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] This abstracted content (or event) is then passed to the agent's Reasoning or inferencing machinery in order to decide what to do with the new content.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] This process combines the event content with the rule-based or knowledge content provided by the user.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] If this process finds a good hit or match in the new content, the agent may use another piece of its machinery to do a more detailed search on the content.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Finally, the agent may decide to take an action based on the new content; for example, to notify the user that an important event has occurred.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] This action is verified by a security function and then given the authority of the user.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The agent makes use of a user-access method to deliver that message to the user.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] If the user confirms that the event is important by acting quickly on the notification, the agent may also employ its learning machinery to increase its weighting for this kind of event.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Bots can act on behalf of their creators to do good as well as bad.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] There are a few ways which bots can be created to demonstrate that they are designed with the best intention and are not built to do harm.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] This is first done by having a bot identify itself in the user-agent HTTP header when communicating with a site.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] The source IP address must also be validated to establish itself as legitimate.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] Next, the bot must also always respect a site's robots.txt file since it has become the standard across most of the web.
[src:kubernetes-operators/software-agent] And like respecting the robots.txt file, bots should shy away from being too aggressive and respect any crawl delay instructions.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] In theoretical computer science, a **finite-state machine** (**FSM**) or **finite-state automaton** (**FSA**, plural: *automata*), **finite automaton**, or simply a **state machine**, is a mathematical model of computation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] It is an abstract machine that can be in exactly one of a finite number of *states* at any given time.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The FSM can change from one state to another in response to some inputs; the change from one state to another is called a *transition*.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] An FSM is defined by a list of its states, its initial state, and the inputs that trigger each transition.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Finite-state machines are of two types—deterministic finite-state machines and non-deterministic finite-state machines.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] For any non-deterministic finite-state machine, an equivalent deterministic one can be constructed.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The behavior of state machines can be observed in many devices in modern society that perform a predetermined sequence of actions depending on a sequence of events with which they are presented.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The finite-state machine has less computational power than some other models of computation such as the Turing machine.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The computational power distinction means there are computational tasks that a Turing machine can do but an FSM cannot.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] This is because an FSM's memory is limited by the number of states it has.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] A finite-state machine has the same computational power as a Turing machine that is restricted such that its head may only perform "read" operations, and always has to move from left to right.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] FSMs are studied in the more general field of automata theory.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] An example of a simple mechanism that can be modeled by a state machine is a turnstile.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] A turnstile, used to control access to subways and amusement park rides, is a gate with three rotating arms at waist height, one across the entryway.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Initially the arms are locked, blocking the entry, preventing patrons from passing through.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Depositing a coin or token in a slot on the turnstile unlocks the arms, allowing a single customer to push through.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] After the customer passes through, the arms are locked again until another coin is inserted.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Considered as a state machine, the turnstile has two possible states: *Locked* and *Unlocked*.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] There are two possible inputs that affect its state: putting a coin in the slot (*coin*) and pushing the arm (*push*).
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] In the locked state, pushing on the arm has no effect; no matter how many times the input *push* is given, it stays in the locked state.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Putting a coin in – that is, giving the machine a *coin* input – shifts the state from *Locked* to *Unlocked*.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] In the unlocked state, putting additional coins in has no effect; that is, giving additional *coin* inputs does not change the state.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] A customer pushing through the arms gives a *push* input and resets the state to *Locked*.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The turnstile state machine can also be represented by a directed graph called a state diagram *(above)*.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Each state is represented by a node (*circle*).
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Edges (*arrows*) show the transitions from one state to another.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Each arrow is labeled with the input that triggers that transition.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] An input that doesn't cause a change of state (such as a *coin* input in the *Unlocked* state) is represented by a circular arrow returning to the original state.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The arrow into the *Locked* node from the black dot indicates it is the initial state.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] A *state* is a description of the status of a system that is waiting to execute a *transition*.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] A transition is a set of actions to be executed when a condition is fulfilled or when an event is received.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] For example, when using an audio system to listen to the radio (the system is in the "radio" state), receiving a "next" stimulus results in moving to the next station.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] When the system is in the "CD" state, the "next" stimulus results in moving to the next track.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Identical stimuli trigger different actions depending on the current state.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Several state-transition table types are used.
