[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] By itself, the table cannot completely describe the action, so it is common to use footnotes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Other related representations may not have this limitation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] For example, an FSM definition including the full action's information is possible using state tables (see also virtual finite-state machine).
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The Unified Modeling Language has a notation for describing state machines.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] UML state machines overcome the limitations of traditional finite-state machines while retaining their main benefits.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] UML state machines introduce the new concepts of hierarchically nested states and orthogonal regions, while extending the notion of actions.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] UML state machines have the characteristics of both Mealy machines and Moore machines.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] They support actions that depend on both the state of the system and the triggering event, as in Mealy machines, as well as entry and exit actions, which are associated with states rather than transitions, as in Moore machines.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] SDL embeds basic data types called "Abstract Data Types", an action language, and an execution semantic in order to make the finite-state machine executable.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] There are a large number of variants to represent an FSM such as the one in figure 3.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] In addition to their use in modeling reactive systems presented here, finite-state machines are significant in many different areas, including electrical engineering, linguistics, computer science, philosophy, biology, mathematics, video game programming, and logic.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Finite-state machines are a class of automata studied in automata theory and the theory of computation.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] In computer science, finite-state machines are widely used in modeling of application behavior (control theory), design of hardware digital systems, software engineering, compilers, network protocols, and computational linguistics.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Finite-state machines can be subdivided into acceptors, classifiers, transducers and sequencers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] A (possibly infinite) set of symbol sequences, called a formal language, is a regular language if there is some acceptor that accepts *exactly* that set.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] For example, the set of binary strings with an even number of zeroes is a regular language (cf.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] 5), while the set of all strings whose length is a prime number is not.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] An acceptor could also be described as defining a language that would contain every string accepted by the acceptor but none of the rejected ones; that language is *accepted* by the acceptor.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] By definition, the languages accepted by acceptors are the regular languages.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The problem of determining the language accepted by a given acceptor is an instance of the algebraic path problem—itself a generalization of the shortest path problem to graphs with edges weighted by the elements of an (arbitrary) semiring.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] An example of an accepting state appears in Fig.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] 5: a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that detects whether the binary input string contains an even number of 0s.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The FSM uses only entry actions, i.e., output depends only on state.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The advantage of the Moore model is a simplification of the behaviour.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The state machine recognizes two commands: "command_open" and "command_close", which trigger state changes.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The entry action (E:) in state "Opening" starts a motor opening the door, the entry action in state "Closing" starts a motor in the other direction closing the door.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] States "Opened" and "Closed" stop the motor when fully opened or closed.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] They signal to the outside world (e.g., to other state machines) the situation: "door is open" or "door is closed".
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The FSM also uses input actions, i.e., output depends on input and state.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The use of a Mealy FSM leads often to a reduction of the number of states.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] There are two input actions (I:): "start motor to close the door if command_close arrives" and "start motor in the other direction to open the door if command_open arrives".
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The "opening" and "closing" intermediate states are not shown.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] A further distinction is between *deterministic* (DFA) and *non-deterministic* (NFA, GNFA) automata.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] In a deterministic automaton, every state has exactly one transition for each possible input.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] In a non-deterministic automaton, an input can lead to one, more than one, or no transition for a given state.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The powerset construction algorithm can transform any nondeterministic automaton into a (usually more complex) deterministic automaton with identical functionality.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] A finite-state machine with only one state is called a "combinatorial FSM".
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] It only allows actions upon transition *into* a state.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] This concept is useful in cases where a number of finite-state machines are required to work together, and when it is convenient to consider a purely combinatorial part as a form of FSM to suit the design tools.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] There are other sets of semantics available to represent state machines.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] For example, there are tools for modeling and designing logic for embedded controllers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] They combine hierarchical state machines (which usually have more than one current state), flow graphs, and truth tables into one language, resulting in a different formalism and set of semantics.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] These charts, like Harel's original state machines, support hierarchically nested states, orthogonal regions, state actions, and transition actions.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] In accordance with the general classification, the following formal definitions are found.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] For both deterministic and non-deterministic FSMs, it is conventional to allow $\delta$ to be a partial function, i.e. $\delta (s,x)$ does not have to be defined for every combination of $s\in S$ and $x\in \Sigma$ .
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] If an FSM M is in a state s , the next symbol is x and $\delta (s,x)$ is not defined, then M can announce an error (i.e. reject the input).
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] This is useful in definitions of general state machines, but less useful when transforming the machine.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Some algorithms in their default form may require total functions.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] That is, each formal language accepted by a finite-state machine is accepted by such a kind of restricted Turing machine, and vice versa.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] If the output function depends on the state and input symbol ( $\omega :S\times \Sigma \rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Mealy model*, and can be modelled as a Mealy machine.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] If the output function depends only on the state ( $\omega :S\rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Moore model*, and can be modelled as a Moore machine.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] A finite-state machine with no output function at all is known as a semiautomaton or transition system.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] If we disregard the first output symbol of a Moore machine, $\omega (s_{0})$ , then it can be readily converted to an output-equivalent Mealy machine by setting the output function of every Mealy transition (i.e. labeling every edge) with the output symbol given of the destination Moore state.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The converse transformation is less straightforward because a Mealy machine state may have different output labels on its incoming transitions (edges).
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Every such state needs to be split in multiple Moore machine states, one for every incident output symbol.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Optimizing an FSM means finding a machine with the minimum number of states that performs the same function.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The fastest known algorithm doing this is the Hopcroft minimization algorithm.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Other techniques include using an implication table, or the Moore reduction procedure.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Additionally, acyclic FSAs can be minimized in linear time.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] In a digital circuit, an FSM may be built using a programmable logic device, a programmable logic controller, logic gates and flip flops or relays.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] More specifically, a hardware implementation requires a register to store state variables, a block of combinational logic that determines the state transition, and a second block of combinational logic that determines the output of an FSM.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] In a *Medvedev machine*, the output is directly connected to the state flip-flops minimizing the time delay between flip-flops and output.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Through state encoding for low power state machines may be optimized to minimize power consumption.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Finite automata are often used in the frontend of programming language compilers.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Such a frontend may comprise several finite-state machines that implement a lexical analyzer and a parser.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] Starting from a sequence of characters, the lexical analyzer builds a sequence of language tokens (such as reserved words, literals, and identifiers) from which the parser builds a syntax tree.
[src:kubernetes-operators/state-machine] The lexical analyzer and the parser handle the regular and context-free parts of the programming language's grammar.
